Platform extends for at least 6m to south-east. Feature situated on a knoll crest. This is the hut that is marked on the crown plan portion 84. Potentially have in situ natural sandstone outcropping that has been integrated into the architecture of the feature eg slab extending out on the southwestern margin of the hearth. Extent of platform currently obscured by leaflProbable south-eastern end of platform evidence by presence of several sandstone blocks assumed to have been part of buildings, footings or supports. Very good excavation potential across entire platform. Excellent potential for detail/sight survey, targeted excavation and interpretation. Occasional fragments of glass and ceramic on platform. Additional scatter recorded separately down north-east. The stones vary in length from .3 to .9 of a metre, average width .15.

Description: Westsouthwest facing hearth. Hearth constructed of mixture of naturally tabular sandstone pieces and dressed modified sandstone and sandstone rubble. In situ stone work on south-eastern, north-eastern, and north-western sides. Stone fall or collapse across centre of hearth and out to north-eastern and north-western sides. Stone fall is consistent with a stonework chimney but it has a height of at least a metre. A piece of corrugated iron in association that may have been part of the flu structure. Indistinct platform extends at least 3 to 4 metres south west. Possibly potentially cut into south-eastern sides to create an artificially layered platform. Additional stone feature a few metres downslope to northwest 7015. 0.53m length of corrugated iron, width is 0.31m. Glass shards found within interior.
Notes: Close proximity (2-3m); perhaps single structure or abutting / associated structures.
